1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,730
- Thanks to Brilliant for sponsoring this video

2
00:00:01,730 --> 00:00:02,750
and supporting my channel.

3
00:00:02,750 --> 00:00:03,583
Hello.

4
00:00:03,583 --> 00:00:04,550
So if you clicked on this video,

5
00:00:04,549 --> 00:00:06,589
you are probably interested in this here

6
00:00:06,589 --> 00:00:08,908
hunk of metal, glass, and silicon

7
00:00:08,910 --> 00:00:11,168
which is a good thing because I have some thoughts

8
00:00:11,167 --> 00:00:13,340
and some experiences that I wanna share with you.

9
00:00:13,340 --> 00:00:14,608
For the past month or so,

10
00:00:14,609 --> 00:00:16,538
I have been doing a lot of my creative work

11
00:00:16,539 --> 00:00:17,599
on this iPad Pro

12
00:00:17,600 --> 00:00:20,490
and in this video I am going to walk you through my setup

13
00:00:20,489 --> 00:00:22,759
and my creative process that I use

14
00:00:22,760 --> 00:00:24,499
while using this device.

15
00:00:24,500 --> 00:00:25,780
I have to say I tried this experiment

16
00:00:25,780 --> 00:00:26,929
once a couple of years ago

17
00:00:26,929 --> 00:00:28,598
and that ended in failure.

18
00:00:28,600 --> 00:00:30,217
The iPad running experience, the time left,

19
00:00:30,216 --> 00:00:32,865
quite a bit to be desired.

20
00:00:32,865 --> 00:00:35,378
But at the urging of my editor, Tony,

21
00:00:35,380 --> 00:00:36,920
who does a lot of his creative writing

22
00:00:36,920 --> 00:00:38,680
and creative work on an iPad Pro,

23
00:00:38,679 --> 00:00:40,098
I decided to give it one more go

24
00:00:40,100 --> 00:00:42,080
and I must say that now this may be

25
00:00:42,079 --> 00:00:44,248
my favorite device for certain parts

26
00:00:44,250 --> 00:00:45,419
of the creative process,

27
00:00:45,420 --> 00:00:46,857
namely reading, research,

28
00:00:46,857 --> 00:00:49,646
and initial drafting when writing scripts.

29
00:00:49,646 --> 00:00:51,939
I still like doing the in depth revision

30
00:00:51,939 --> 00:00:54,189
and editing and final drafting on my computer,

31
00:00:54,189 --> 00:00:56,668
it feels a little bit more precise there,

32
00:00:56,668 --> 00:00:58,797
but for initial stream of consciousness writing,

33
00:00:58,798 --> 00:01:01,375
for getting a first draft down on the virtual page,

34
00:01:01,377 --> 00:01:03,320
I really, really like this.

35
00:01:03,320 --> 00:01:04,800
So, I am gonna organize this video

36
00:01:04,799 --> 00:01:06,228
by each of the three stages.

37
00:01:06,230 --> 00:01:07,970
Reading, research, and writing.

38
00:01:07,969 --> 00:01:09,079
And for each of those stages,

39
00:01:09,079 --> 00:01:10,829
I'm gonna show you the setup that I'm using,

40
00:01:10,829 --> 00:01:12,801
along with one unique app for each of the stages

41
00:01:12,802 --> 00:01:14,164
and how I use it

42
00:01:14,164 --> 00:01:16,780
and maybe give you an overall kind of verdict

43
00:01:16,780 --> 00:01:18,350
on whether or not this may be worth

44
00:01:18,349 --> 00:01:19,839
your time and money.

45
00:01:19,840 --> 00:01:21,699
So let's start with the reading stage.

46
00:01:21,698 --> 00:01:23,379
Earlier this year I talked about

47
00:01:23,379 --> 00:01:24,921
how I take notes from physical books

48
00:01:24,921 --> 00:01:27,235
using those little colored flags to mark my spot

49
00:01:27,236 --> 00:01:30,180
and by actually underlining and highlighting

50
00:01:30,180 --> 00:01:31,214
parts of physical books.

51
00:01:31,215 --> 00:01:35,280
This and specifically an app called Readwise

52
00:01:35,280 --> 00:01:38,210
which is on iPad, iPhone,

53
00:01:38,209 --> 00:01:39,499
and it's on browser extensions,

54
00:01:39,500 --> 00:01:40,420
it's basically on everything,

55
00:01:40,420 --> 00:01:43,270
has me now using Kindle once more

56
00:01:43,269 --> 00:01:44,904
and there is a very good reason for that.

57
00:01:44,906 --> 00:01:47,477
You can actually highlight passages in Kindle books

58
00:01:47,477 --> 00:01:49,281
using the Apple pencil or using your thumb

59
00:01:49,281 --> 00:01:51,470
if you don't wanna buy an Apple pencil

60
00:01:51,469 --> 00:01:53,039
and in the past it's always gone

61
00:01:53,040 --> 00:01:55,290
to your Kindle highlights for that particular book.

62
00:01:55,290 --> 00:01:57,399
But Readwise actually syncs those highlights

63
00:01:57,400 --> 00:02:00,250
from Kindle to a Readwise app

64
00:02:00,250 --> 00:02:01,820
where you can look at your highlights every day,

65
00:02:01,819 --> 00:02:03,059
you can do daily review,

66
00:02:03,060 --> 00:02:04,570
you can even do spaced repetition

67
00:02:04,569 --> 00:02:06,079
style memorization exercises,

68
00:02:06,079 --> 00:02:09,243
but Readwise has integration with Notion

69
00:02:09,243 --> 00:02:11,504
which means that now all of my Kindle highlights

70
00:02:11,504 --> 00:02:13,399
go to a Notion database

71
00:02:13,401 --> 00:02:15,330
and I can put my regular book notes

72
00:02:15,330 --> 00:02:16,519
in there with my highlights

73
00:02:16,520 --> 00:02:19,149
and I find that that is a great process

74
00:02:19,150 --> 00:02:21,009
for doing research which I'll talk about a bit later.

75
00:02:21,008 --> 00:02:23,008
First, a few words about the overall hardware

76
00:02:23,008 --> 00:02:25,209
as it pertains to reading.

77
00:02:25,210 --> 00:02:27,050
I went with the 11 inch Pro

78
00:02:27,050 --> 00:02:28,660
which is quite a bit lighter

79
00:02:28,659 --> 00:02:30,989
and quite a bit smaller than the 12.9 inch

80
00:02:30,990 --> 00:02:32,330
which was the one I bought back when

81
00:02:32,330 --> 00:02:34,239
I got the first generation iPad Pro

82
00:02:34,240 --> 00:02:36,159
and I have to say the size difference

83
00:02:36,159 --> 00:02:37,350
is actually really nice.

84
00:02:37,350 --> 00:02:39,391
I have not missed the additional screen real estate

85
00:02:39,393 --> 00:02:41,877
and the difference in size and the weight reduction

86
00:02:41,877 --> 00:02:44,009
is a really, really nice thing while reading.

87
00:02:44,009 --> 00:02:46,469
Anyway, onto step two of my creative process

88
00:02:46,471 --> 00:02:47,860
which is research.

89
00:02:47,860 --> 00:02:49,947
So in addition to reading a lot of books on the Kindle app,

90
00:02:49,947 --> 00:02:51,640
reading a lot of physical books,

91
00:02:51,639 --> 00:02:53,797
I also do a lot of article based research

92
00:02:53,799 --> 00:02:55,083
for writing my videos.

93
00:02:55,084 --> 00:02:57,568
I was digging into tons and tons of interviews

94
00:02:57,568 --> 00:02:59,338
with people like William Gibson

95
00:02:59,340 --> 00:03:01,340
who wrote "New Romancer," with Steve Jobs,

96
00:03:01,340 --> 00:03:04,469
tons of people in the research for my last video

97
00:03:04,469 --> 00:03:06,553
and there is a specific app on the iPad,

98
00:03:06,555 --> 00:03:07,809
also on the iPhone,

99
00:03:07,810 --> 00:03:09,453
that really, really helped with that process.

100
00:03:09,454 --> 00:03:12,630
It's called Command and it is an alternative browser

101
00:03:12,629 --> 00:03:14,589
to Safari that actually allows you

102
00:03:14,590 --> 00:03:17,179
to highlight what's on the page.

103
00:03:17,180 --> 00:03:19,300
Now there is a Readwise extension that works

104
00:03:19,300 --> 00:03:20,850
with mobile Safari so if you want to

105
00:03:20,849 --> 00:03:23,069
highlight a passage and sync it to Readwise

106
00:03:23,069 --> 00:03:24,689
in mobile Safari you can do that,

107
00:03:24,689 --> 00:03:26,658
but Command actually takes it a step further.

108
00:03:26,658 --> 00:03:29,628
Number one, there is far less friction in the process.

109
00:03:29,628 --> 00:03:31,209
With the Safari version,

110
00:03:31,210 --> 00:03:32,480
you gotta highlight the text

111
00:03:32,479 --> 00:03:33,583
and then you gotta go to the share menu,

112
00:03:33,585 --> 00:03:35,430
you gotta hit the Readwise button,

113
00:03:35,430 --> 00:03:37,361
there's a whole big process you have to go through.

114
00:03:37,361 --> 00:03:39,534
With Command, you simply highlight

115
00:03:39,534 --> 00:03:41,338
whatever it is you wanna highlight

116
00:03:41,340 --> 00:03:42,850
and you hit highlight.

117
00:03:42,849 --> 00:03:44,589
That will automatically sync it to Readwise

118
00:03:44,590 --> 00:03:46,039
which again syncs it to Notion

119
00:03:46,039 --> 00:03:47,182
if you have the integration set up.

120
00:03:47,182 --> 00:03:49,492
So that means in Notion I have a centralized

121
00:03:49,492 --> 00:03:51,718
database of all of my highlights,

122
00:03:51,719 --> 00:03:54,808
all of my research from not only Kindle books,

123
00:03:54,810 --> 00:03:56,050
not only physical books

124
00:03:56,050 --> 00:03:57,312
because you can actually take pictures

125
00:03:57,312 --> 00:03:59,176
of physical books and highlight that way in Readwise,

126
00:03:59,175 --> 00:04:01,473
but also all the articles I read.

127
00:04:01,474 --> 00:04:03,319
It gives me a centralized repository

128
00:04:03,319 --> 00:04:05,261
for everything that I might wanna reference for a video

129
00:04:05,262 --> 00:04:07,560
and then I can use the back link system

130
00:04:07,560 --> 00:04:09,648
while doing my research in my initial drafting process

131
00:04:09,649 --> 00:04:13,230
to create links to those research sources.

132
00:04:13,229 --> 00:04:14,219
It is awesome.

133
00:04:14,219 --> 00:04:16,009
And beyond just the Readwise integration,

134
00:04:16,009 --> 00:04:17,414
there are a couple of other features of note.

135
00:04:17,415 --> 00:04:19,280
One is tab groupings.

136
00:04:19,279 --> 00:04:21,779
You can actually create different sets of open tabs

137
00:04:21,779 --> 00:04:23,851
so you can group your tabs by different research projects.

138
00:04:23,853 --> 00:04:26,312
That's very helpful for somebody like me

139
00:04:26,312 --> 00:04:28,092
who often has a few different research projects

140
00:04:28,093 --> 00:04:29,093
going all at once

141
00:04:29,095 --> 00:04:32,047
and when you highlight a passage on a page

142
00:04:32,048 --> 00:04:33,875
and then reload that page later,

143
00:04:33,875 --> 00:04:35,750
it stays highlighted.

144
00:04:35,750 --> 00:04:36,870
This actually wasn't something

145
00:04:36,870 --> 00:04:38,600
that was originally in the browser's build,

146
00:04:38,600 --> 00:04:40,136
but I asked the developer to implement it

147
00:04:40,137 --> 00:04:41,1000
and they were really, really quick about it.

148
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:45,035
So now if I've got that database of Notion links

149
00:04:45,035 --> 00:04:46,702
and I wanna open up the original article

150
00:04:46,702 --> 00:04:48,810
to see a highlight in context,

151
00:04:48,810 --> 00:04:51,039
I can go right to that highlight,

152
00:04:51,040 --> 00:04:52,249
see it in yellow,

153
00:04:52,250 --> 00:04:53,730
and then you know, get the context

154
00:04:53,730 --> 00:04:55,430
from wherever it was in the article

155
00:04:55,430 --> 00:04:56,263
or the interview.

156
00:04:56,262 --> 00:04:58,927
That's really, really nice for good, deep research.

157
00:04:58,927 --> 00:05:00,469
And that brings us to the final part

158
00:05:00,470 --> 00:05:01,986
of the creative process that I do on this iPad

159
00:05:01,985 --> 00:05:04,280
which is the initial drafting for all of my scripts,

160
00:05:04,281 --> 00:05:06,389
along with any sort of initial stage writing.

161
00:05:06,389 --> 00:05:08,929
For instance, I've been getting up every morning

162
00:05:08,930 --> 00:05:10,359
and trying to write every day

163
00:05:10,360 --> 00:05:12,003
because I find that when I have a daily writing process,

164
00:05:12,004 --> 00:05:14,116
even if it's a stream of consciousness writing,

165
00:05:14,117 --> 00:05:16,270
even if it's not stuff that I'm gonna use,

166
00:05:16,269 --> 00:05:17,859
my writing gets more interesting.

167
00:05:17,860 --> 00:05:19,210
I tend to use more stories,

168
00:05:19,209 --> 00:05:20,588
I tend to use more analogies,

169
00:05:20,589 --> 00:05:21,718
it just gets better,

170
00:05:21,720 --> 00:05:22,752
so I wanna keep that habit up

171
00:05:22,752 --> 00:05:24,028
and I've been doing that every day

172
00:05:24,028 --> 00:05:26,528
in a little daily writing notebook in Notion.

173
00:05:26,529 --> 00:05:29,199
And that is actually where I do all of my writing.

174
00:05:29,201 --> 00:05:30,864
We've got a content ideas area

175
00:05:30,865 --> 00:05:33,030
where whenever I have a video idea,

176
00:05:33,029 --> 00:05:33,959
I'll write it down there,

177
00:05:33,959 --> 00:05:35,608
I write down some initial notes

178
00:05:35,610 --> 00:05:37,362
and then whenever we know we're gonna create a video,

179
00:05:37,362 --> 00:05:40,277
I spawn a video project from a template we've created

180
00:05:40,278 --> 00:05:41,980
which has a deep research area

181
00:05:41,980 --> 00:05:43,748
and then a scripting area.

182
00:05:43,749 --> 00:05:45,654
Now there's one little gripe that I have

183
00:05:45,653 --> 00:05:47,288
about Notion on the iPad.

184
00:05:47,288 --> 00:05:49,409
Well, at least one that I'll talk about here

185
00:05:49,410 --> 00:05:51,459
and that is the fact that you cannot do

186
00:05:51,459 --> 00:05:54,159
split screen of the exact same app

187
00:05:54,160 --> 00:05:55,559
with Notion right now.

188
00:05:55,560 --> 00:05:57,680
I believe that certain apps now have that capability

189
00:05:57,680 --> 00:05:59,400
where you can put two instances of the

190
00:05:59,399 --> 00:06:00,749
same app side by side,

191
00:06:00,750 --> 00:06:02,530
but the dedicated Notion app

192
00:06:02,529 --> 00:06:03,940
does not currently have that ability.

193
00:06:03,942 --> 00:06:06,361
But there is a workaround for that.

194
00:06:06,360 --> 00:06:10,058
Because Notion is essentially just a web app in a wrapper,

195
00:06:10,060 --> 00:06:11,630
you can open up one instance of Notion

196
00:06:11,629 --> 00:06:12,609
in the Notion app

197
00:06:12,610 --> 00:06:14,230
and then open it up in Safari

198
00:06:14,230 --> 00:06:15,178
and put it right next to it.

199
00:06:15,177 --> 00:06:17,031
So I've done that for when I wanna do

200
00:06:17,031 --> 00:06:18,976
some initial scripting, initial drafting,

201
00:06:18,976 --> 00:06:21,213
but I wanna have a bunch of research

202
00:06:21,213 --> 00:06:23,238
to the side as well

203
00:06:23,240 --> 00:06:25,522
and I can independently scroll through the research

204
00:06:25,521 --> 00:06:27,065
while also writing my draft.

205
00:06:27,067 --> 00:06:29,010
I've experimented with having the research

206
00:06:29,009 --> 00:06:31,612
next to the drafting area in one page of Notion

207
00:06:31,612 --> 00:06:34,157
but it means that if I wanna scroll to see something

208
00:06:34,158 --> 00:06:36,523
in the research I am losing my place

209
00:06:36,524 --> 00:06:37,590
where I was writing.

210
00:06:37,589 --> 00:06:39,338
So this hack is a little bit better

211
00:06:39,338 --> 00:06:41,169
than doing it that way.

212
00:06:41,170 --> 00:06:42,920
Now while we're talking about the writing process,

213
00:06:42,920 --> 00:06:44,369
I gotta talk about the keyboard a little bit.

214
00:06:44,370 --> 00:06:47,090
This is great, again, for resting in my lap

215
00:06:47,089 --> 00:06:48,069
when I wanna read a book,

216
00:06:48,069 --> 00:06:49,839
but how good is it for actually writing.

217
00:06:49,841 --> 00:06:52,289
Well the first I'll say is that going with

218
00:06:52,290 --> 00:06:54,922
the 11 inch version involves a bit of a compromise.

219
00:06:54,922 --> 00:06:57,691
The full size 12.9 inch version of the iPad Pro

220
00:06:57,690 --> 00:07:00,799
has a full size keyboard on the Magic Keyboard case.

221
00:07:00,800 --> 00:07:02,406
This one does not.

222
00:07:02,406 --> 00:07:05,409
They don't have a bunch of room here,

223
00:07:05,410 --> 00:07:06,928
so they had to shrink some of the keys,

224
00:07:06,927 --> 00:07:08,205
including the dash key here,

225
00:07:08,206 --> 00:07:10,262
the shift keys are a little bit smaller,

226
00:07:10,264 --> 00:07:11,528
the return keys are a bit smaller

227
00:07:11,528 --> 00:07:13,516
and initially I thought this was going to be an issue.

228
00:07:13,516 --> 00:07:15,376
My editor told me that he got used to it,

229
00:07:15,377 --> 00:07:17,686
but my hands are kind of big

230
00:07:17,685 --> 00:07:18,715
so I was a bit worried about it.

231
00:07:18,716 --> 00:07:20,524
But actually after a couple of days,

232
00:07:20,524 --> 00:07:23,290
I got used to this and I'm able to context switch

233
00:07:23,290 --> 00:07:25,098
between this and my laptop

234
00:07:25,100 --> 00:07:27,810
and my mechanical keyboard on my desktop pretty easily.

235
00:07:27,810 --> 00:07:29,384
So that's not really a big deal.

236
00:07:29,384 --> 00:07:33,494
The main thing that I see as a benefit with the iPad is

237
00:07:33,494 --> 00:07:36,110
I don't have Slack on this.

238
00:07:36,110 --> 00:07:37,390
I don't have email on this.

239
00:07:37,389 --> 00:07:38,838
I don't have social media on this.

240
00:07:38,839 --> 00:07:41,638
This is kind of a single context device.

241
00:07:41,639 --> 00:07:43,003
I use it for learning,

242
00:07:43,004 --> 00:07:44,580
I use it for research,

243
00:07:44,579 --> 00:07:46,449
I use it for content creation.

244
00:07:46,449 --> 00:07:47,519
That is it.

245
00:07:47,519 --> 00:07:51,690
And I value having tools that keep me separate

246
00:07:51,692 --> 00:07:53,880
from the bits of my work that are

247
00:07:53,879 --> 00:07:55,359
a bit more tempting to get into

248
00:07:55,360 --> 00:07:56,809
when I don't wanna be doing my writing

249
00:07:56,809 --> 00:07:58,622
or when I don't wanna be doing deep research.

250
00:07:58,622 --> 00:08:00,069
So that is quite valuable to me.

251
00:08:00,069 --> 00:08:01,736
And like I said earlier,

252
00:08:01,737 --> 00:08:03,602
when I tried this experiment a couple years ago,

253
00:08:03,603 --> 00:08:05,920
the software was really not up to snuff,

254
00:08:05,920 --> 00:08:06,814
the experience wasn't good.

255
00:08:06,814 --> 00:08:09,165
Now I think they've rectified a lot of that.

256
00:08:09,165 --> 00:08:11,411
The Magic Keyboard is a big improvement on its own,

257
00:08:11,413 --> 00:08:14,130
but the addition of the touch pad here

258
00:08:14,129 --> 00:08:16,435
and the touch pad drivers in iOS means that

259
00:08:16,437 --> 00:08:19,413
this kind of operates almost like a laptop.

260
00:08:19,413 --> 00:08:20,945
There are still certain compromises,

261
00:08:20,944 --> 00:08:23,195
but for my purposes in content creation,

262
00:08:23,197 --> 00:08:24,963
none of those compromises matter.

263
00:08:24,963 --> 00:08:27,378
Beyond that, Notion has all of the same

264
00:08:27,379 --> 00:08:29,050
keyboard shortcuts I'm used to.

265
00:08:29,050 --> 00:08:30,852
I remember that being a huge frustration point

266
00:08:30,851 --> 00:08:32,738
when I was trying this before.

267
00:08:32,740 --> 00:08:34,560
A lot of the apps I would use on a desktop

268
00:08:34,559 --> 00:08:35,887
either weren't on the iPad

269
00:08:35,889 --> 00:08:37,080
or if they were,

270
00:08:37,080 --> 00:08:39,459
the keyboard shortcuts were just not there half the time

271
